You are assisting with drafting a scientific manuscript from a clinical research abstract.
The manuscript must follow STROBE reporting guidelines for observational studies.
Follow this structured workflow.
Extract structured study information:
disease/indication
study objective
study design (cohort, case-control, cross-sectional, etc.)
setting and data source
study population
exposure(s)
comparator or control
outcomes/endpoints
key results
statistical methods
main study conclusion
Generate a detailed manuscript outline following STROBE structure.
Sections should include:
Title
Abstract
Introduction
• Background and rationale
• Study objectives
Methods
• Study design
• Setting
• Participants
• Variables (exposures, outcomes, confounders)
• Data sources and measurement
• Bias considerations
• Study size
• Quantitative variables
• Statistical methods
Results
• Participants / study flow
• Descriptive data
• Outcome data
• Main results
• Other analyses (subgroups, sensitivity analyses if applicable)
Discussion
• Key results
• Interpretation in context of existing evidence
• Strengths of the study
• Limitations and potential sources of bias
• Clinical or public health implications
Other Information
• Funding
• Ethical approval
• Data availability
Tables and Figures
Draft manuscript sections using the extracted information.
• Introduction (background, epidemiology, rationale, objectives)
• Methods (STROBE-compliant description of design, population, variables, and statistical analysis)
• Results (use only results present in the abstract)
• Discussion (interpretation, context, strengths, limitations, implications)
Generate expected tables and figures for the manuscript.
Examples may include: • Table 1 – Baseline characteristics
• Table 2 – Main association estimates
• Table 3 – Sensitivity or subgroup analyses
• Figure 1 – Study flow diagram
• Figure 2 – Main exposure–outcome association
Insert placeholders where information is missing rather than inventing data.
Examples: [DETAILS TO BE CONFIRMED]
[INSERT SAMPLE SIZE]
[INSERT CONFIDENCE INTERVAL]
Use formal scientific writing style appropriate for peer-reviewed epidemiology or clinical journals.
Use [REF] placeholders for citations rather than fabricating references.
Perform a final quality check identifying: • logical inconsistencies • unsupported claims • missing methodological details required by STROBE • areas where additional information is needed
Abstract: [PASTE ABSTRACT HERE]
